Date: 29 Mar 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Health Canada - SARS website 29 Mar 2003 [edited]


Update 14 - SARS 29 Mar 2003 5:00 PM

As of 29 Mar 2003, Health Canada has received reports of 37 cases of severe
acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) in Ontario, British Columbia and
Manitoba. There have been 3 deaths in Canada. All Canadian cases have
occurred in persons who have traveled to Asia or had contact with SARS
cases in the household or in a health-care setting. The information
contained in this update is based on the best available information Health
Canada has at this time.

The details of the cases to date are as follows:

Ontario: 35 total cases. All cases have occurred in persons who have
traveled to Asia or had contact with SARS cases in the household or in a
health-care setting.

British Columbia: one person has been hospitalized with SARS after
returning from travel in southeast Asia.

Manitoba: one person has been hospitalized with SARS after returning from
travel in southeast Asia.

Due to the mounting concern about transmission of the SARS agent in
non-hospital and community settings in the City of Hanoi, Vietnam; the
People's Republic of China including the Hong Kong SAR; and Singapore,
Health Canada recommends that persons planning to travel to these areas
should defer all travel until further notice. Health Canada also recommends
alternate routing be considered, when possible, if a traveller is
transiting through the People's Republic of China including the Hong Kong
SAR; City of Hanoi, Vietnam; or Singapore. Health Canada is aware that
health authorities in these affected areas are making concerted efforts to
contain the spread of SARS in their populations. Given the uncertainties of
the current situation, Health Canada believes it is prudent to await the
outcome of national and international control measures before undertaking
travel to these destinations.

On 29 Mar 2003, Health Canada deployed 2 additional staff to assist Toronto
Public Health and the Ontario Ministry of Health with the investigation of
SARS cases. This now brings the total number of Health Canada staff
assisting in Ontario to 7. The department has also provided guidelines for
infection control and recommendations on actions for public health settings.

On 27 Mar 2003, the World Health Organization (WHO) recommended new
measures, related to international travel aimed at reducing the risk of
further international spread of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS).
The measures proposed by WHO on the screening of passengers presenting for
international travel are under active consideration by Health
Canada. Health Canada has discussed this issue with the local airport
authority in Toronto and we are putting together a plan. Health Canada is
hoping to have something in place in Toronto over the course of the weekend.

It is important to note that airlines operating international flights in
and out of Canada have been carrying out long-standing procedures to
prevent sick passengers from getting on airplanes.

--
