Correction: The Department of Microbiology, Hong Kong University
----------------------------------------------------------------
I just wish to inform you of another correction: The virologist at Hong
Kong University (HKU)is Prof. Malik Peiris (not "Professor Mark Peiris" as
stated incorrectly by the Moderator in the ProMED-mail post entitled SARS -
worldwide (16): etiology 20030328.0774). And Prof. K. Y. Yuen is the Head
of the Department of Microbiology of University of Hong Kong.

--
Eugene Yeung
Government Virus Unit, HKSAR
<eugene@technoworks.net>

[ProMED-mail regrets this error in transcription and welcomes
the opportunity to set the record straight. - Mod.CP]

[Today's reports represent an increase in 65 cases and one death since
yesterday's report, of which there are 45 new cases reported in Hong
Kong. Due to a time zone difference, the WHO statistics for the USA
represent the number of cases reported yesterday (28 Mar 2003), whereas in
the CDC update presented in [4] there is an increase in 3 cases in the
USA. With the exception of Hong Kong and mainland China, it still appears
as though transmission is via close contact with active cases of SARS
either in the health care setting or household contacts. Information on
the epidemiology of the cases in mainland China is still pending, and in
Hong Kong there appears to be transmission in a housing complex, but the
degree of contact between the cases is still under study.
